		<br />
		<h3 style="text-align:center;">
			What is wrong with the current publishing model?
		</h3>

		<h4 style="text-align:center;">The gift of exchange</h4>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society is the world's
			longest-running scientific journal and was established in 1665. The Royal
			Society was steadfast in its not-yet-popular belief that science could
			only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed
			by experimental evidence.
		</p>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			As a result, for nearly 300 years, a system known as the "gift of
			exchange" was in place, in which almost all scholarly work, with the
			exception of proprietary research, was made freely available to the
			public.
		</p>
		<h4 style="text-align:center;">Commercialising academic research</h4>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Unfortunately, this system is no longer in place today. In the 1960’s and
			1970’s commercial publishers recognised that academic publishing was
			commercially viable and started to selectively purchase top-quality
			journals owned by non-profit academic societies. They saw an opportunity
			to profit from the distribution of publicly financed research. Since the
			demand for academic journals is relatively inelastic, especially in the
			case of university libraries, publishers were able to increase prices
			significantly allowing for astronomical profit margins.
		</p>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			With almost 55% of the market share in 2020, four major publishers namely
			Elsevier, Springer, Wiley, and Taylor & Francis dominate the academic
			journal industry. These powerful publishing houses have a history of
			merging, acquiring, and launching new journals to diversify their journal
			portfolios. Modern academic publishing is based on a unique economic model
			in which all of the necessary publishing inputs are provided free of
			charge. As part of a larger scholarly endeavour, academics provide a key
			economic input that is then commercialised by publishers as part of the
			process of dissemination.
		</p>
		<h4 style="text-align:center;">The Serials Crisis</h4>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			In the United States, commercial journal publishers hiked prices by 310%
			between 1975 and 1995. Budgets for university libraries normally only
			increase in line with CPI inflation, which in the United States was 183%
			between 1975 and 1995. As a result, the serials crisis began in the 1990s,
			when an increasing number of university library budgets were unable to
			keep up with rising journal prices. Overall, the ratio of journal
			expenditures to total library materials expenditures climbed from 53% in
			1986 to 73% in 2011, with expenditures on other categories of resources,
			such as monographs, falling by 21%.

			<div class="barchart-holder">
				<div id="expend_title_holder">
					<div class="graph-heading">
						Distribution of expenditures in academic materials budgets in the
						United States
					</div>
					<div id="expend_legend">
						<span><span class="dot1"></span> 2010</span>
						<span><span class="dot2"></span> 2013</span>
