						</div>
					</span>
				</div>
			</div>
			<br />
		</p>
		<h4 style="text-align:center;">The Big Deal</h4>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			'The Big Deal' was a significant event in academic publishing history
			where instead of selling individual journals to university libraries,
			publishers grouped them into bundle deals, thereby granting them access to
			entire journal collections in exchange for a fixed yearly subscription
			fee. It was cleverly designed to ensure libraries had either all or none
			of the journals. This made publishers become more profitable with the
			example of Elsevier's operating profits climbing by more than 400% between
			1991 and 2013, and its profit margin never dipping below 30% throughout
			the period.
		</p>
		<h4 style="text-align:center;">Taking a stand</h4>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Following a dispute over access to research publications, Norway and
			Sweden along with individual universities from other countries have
			discontinued their contracts with the likes of Elsevier. This was an
			attempt for a sustainable transition to Open Access (OA). However, the OA
			movement has become a crisis itself in that commercial publishers have
			appeased public scrutiny and provided hybrid journals that are both
			subscription based and open access model that has proven to charge higher
			prices on average than standalone open access journals.
		</p>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			The academic society has come up with vast solutions to combat the
			unsustainable rise in prices one of which is the library-press
			partnerships. The library has taken on a new role in scholarly publishing,
			forming partnerships with university presses to encourage universities to
			develop comprehensive publishing plans that draw on the expertise and
			resources of several departments within the institution, including the
			library, press, and academic computing centre. In the more liberating
			space, Sci-Hub pulls paid scientific publications from major publishers
			and makes them freely available to the public. Sci-Hub was founded on the
			notion that granting copyrights to scientific works and placing paywalls
			on them stifles society's advancement.
		</p>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Given this premise, the development of Aaron’s Kit was created to
			complement society’s actions by decentralising scholarly work to ensure
			censorship resistance to fight back and honour Aaron Swartz Guerilla Open
			Access Manifesto “You have a duty to share it with the world”.
		</p>
