		<h3 style="text-align:center;">What is Open Access?</h3>

		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Open Access (OA) is a broad international movement and seeks to grant free
			and immediate online access to academic research outputs such as journal
			articles, books and data. It is in opposition to the traditional
			subscription based publishing model, which allows users to access
			scholarly information by purchasing a subscription (usually via
			libraries).
		</p>

		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			A publication is considered open access when there are no financial,
			legal, or technical restrictions to accessing it. Thus, within the legal
			agreements, anybody may freely read, download, copy, search for, and use a
			publication in any way. Many journals now offer various "open access like"
			models in which they charge researchers a once-off fee to make their
			scholarly output freely accessible.
		</p>
		<p style="text-align:justify" class="margin-p">
			Even though Open Access has become very popular over the past several
			years and is a positive development, it is not without its drawbacks:
		</p>
		<CtaCardSection>
			<p><u><b>Article Processing Charges (APCs)</b></u></p>
			<p>
				Researchers often have to pay substantial costs to journals to make
				their research freely available. APC charges vary, and cost on average
				$1000, where the most prestigious journals charge upwards of $5000.
			</p>
			<p><u><b>Scarse Open Access journals</b></u></p>
			<p>
				The number of Open Access or hybrid journals vary greatly across
				disciplines. Some disciplines have very few and often not enough.
			</p>
			<p><u><b>Predatory publishing</b></u></p>
			<p>
				Predatory journals, a term used for journals of dubious quality, slow
				down the open access movement as their continuous spamming of
				researchers may taint their perception of open access.
			</p>
		</CtaCardSection>
